<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-106-268  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 106 268.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 13 1989 v6 n10 p70(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Keeping track of hazards. (Human Resources)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Personnel managementMicrocomputersUnited States. Occupational Safety and Health AdministrationGovernment RegulationHazardous Materials.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Tracking worker health and safety by computer. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>In today's workplace there are so many toxic hazards around, you might need aPC to keep track of them all.andP;  Medical advances have revealed employee perilnot only in obvious culprits such as industrial solvents, but also in itemslike sawdust and laser-printer toner.andM;This month, the federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA)initiated landmark regulations that require employers to protect employeesfrom dangerous substances.andP;  Besides mandating physical protection, OSHA andother federal, state and local agencies are now requiring all-time highlevels of toxic-materials recordkeeping.andM;One obligation that companies have is managing ''material-safety datasheets'' (MSDSs) that arrive in hard-copy form with hazardous products.andP;  Thesheets indicate what reporting is required for each product, and each must beshown to all employees who work with a product.andP;  PC packages, such as CHRISPlus from HRD Software of Amherst, Mass., and MSDS Engine from GeniumPublishing Corp. of Schenectady, N.Y., are MSDS databases that help fulfillreporting requirements.andM;MSDSs may be built into software (Occupational Health Services Inc. of NewYork offers a compact disk, read-only memory disk with MSDS data on 10,000substances) or vendors can provide MSDS data-entry.andP;  To inform workers, acompany might install a public-access PC with an MSDS database, said AlanMacenski, who uses PCs in the Health andamp; Safety Department at TRW Inc., ofRedondo Beach, Calif.andM;Even where reporting isn't mandated, it's prudent for an employer to recordworker exposures -- to keep them healthy and to reduce its own exposure tolawsuits and penalties.andP;  OHEDS, from Web-Wolf Data Systems Inc. of McLean,Va., is a stand-alone package that records employee health histories andschedules tests to monitor exposure to hazards.andM;Spectrum Human Resource Systems Corp. of Denver soon will release anIndustrial Health and Safety Module for its PC-based HR/2000 human-resourcesinformation system, which will integrate toxic-exposure data into employeerecords.andM;A 1987 survey of members of the Association of Human Resources Professionalsshowed that just 20 percent have systems in place for tracking toxicsubstances, but an association spokesman said the subject is gainingattention.andP;  Dick Frantzreb, who publishes the Personnel Software Census inRoseville, Calif., said there are about 50 micro-based packages fortoxic-safety applications.andP;  There's even a package for choosing protectiveclothing, from Arthur D. Little Inc. of Cambridge, Mass.andO;</TEXT></DOC>